    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1965-11-23T19:26:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1965-11-23T19:26:00-05:00" n="256"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d256">
                <head>256. Circular Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss>
                    to <gloss type="to">Embassies</gloss> in Africa<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d256fn1">Source: Department of State, Central Files, <gloss
                            target="#t_POL1">POL</gloss> 15–1 GHANA. Confidential. Drafted by
                        Officer in Charge of Ghana Affairs <persName corresp="#p_SRP1">Robert P.
                            Smith</persName>, and Hendrik Van Oss of AFW; cleared by <persName
                            corresp="#p_TWC1">Trimble</persName>, Donald J. Kent of <gloss
                            target="#t_AF1">AF</gloss>/<gloss target="#t_P1">P</gloss>, Robert F.
                        Andrew of <gloss target="#t_INRRAF1">INR/RAF</gloss>, and Ben Thirkeild of
                            <gloss target="#t_P1">P</gloss>/ON. Approved by Williams. Repeated to
                        London.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1965-11-23T19:26:00-05:00">November 23, 1965, 7:26 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1002. Embassies pass Consulates.</p>
                <p rend="flushleft">
                    <hi rend="italic">
                        <persName corresp="#p_NK2">Nkrumah</persName>’s Book</hi>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Following for your discretionary use with senior officials host
                        govt.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>In Oct Pres <persName corresp="#p_NK2">Nkrumah</persName> of Ghana
                        published book entitled <hi rend="italic">Neo-Colonialism—The Last Stage of
                            Imperialism</hi>, and gave copies to African chiefs of state attending
                            <gloss target="#t_OAU1">OAU</gloss> conference at Accra. Book contains
                        unmistakably hostile charges against USG motives, actions, and intentions
                        and is clear and comprehensive statement of <persName corresp="#p_NK2"
                            >Nkrumah</persName>’s fundamental anti-Western, anti-US bias. His
                        charges against Peace Corps, <gloss target="#t_USIA1">USIA</gloss> and
                            <gloss target="#t_CIA1">CIA</gloss> have already intensified Ghanaian
                        press attacks on these agencies and constitute official sanction for
                        continuing attacks.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Asst Secy Williams summoned Ghanaian <gloss target="#t_Amb1">Amb</gloss>
                        to US Ribeiro Nov 18 and lodged stern oral protest of book. Ribeiro was also
                        handed aide-memoire<note n="2" xml:id="d256fn2">Dated November 17. (Ibid.,
                                <gloss target="#t_POL1">POL</gloss> GHANA–US)</note> (1) stating USG
                        views <persName corresp="#p_NK2">Nkrumah</persName>’s attacks on US in book
                        with profound concern; (2) noting unprecedented nature such an attack by
                        Head of State of friendly country; (3) informing <gloss target="#t_GOG1"
                            >GOG</gloss> that book’s hostility and its provocative and anti-American
                        tone are “deeply disturbing and offensive” to USG; and (4) holding <gloss
                            target="#t_GOG1">GOG</gloss> fully responsible for whatever consequences
                        book’s publication may have.</item>
                    <pb facs="0500" n="452" xml:id="pg_452"/>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>Gov emphasized to Ribeiro we could not now foresee all consequences of
                        book but that these would “undoubtedly become evident in due course.”</item>
                    <label>5.</label>
                    <item>Dept recognizes book thus far has had little or no impact in Africa and
                        wants avoid any action which would unduly publicize it, or make USG appear
                        overreacting. Above info should therefore be used cautiously, in low key and
                        only if you deem appropriate in local context.</item>
                    <label>6.</label>
                    <item>While Dept under no illusions that US response will alter <persName
                            corresp="#p_NK2">Nkrumah</persName>’s views, we believe it important
                        make clear that attack of this nature by Head of State unacceptable. Failure
                        to act may make more credible <persName corresp="#p_NK2"
                        >Nkrumah</persName>’s position with other African governments that strong
                        anti-US and anti-Western posture has no serious disadvantages.</item>
                    <label>7.</label>
                    <item>On Nov 20 <gloss target="#t_Emb1">Emb</gloss> Accra delivered note to
                            <gloss target="#t_GOG1">GOG</gloss> MinFonAffairs turning down <gloss
                            target="#t_GOG1">GOG</gloss>’s long-pending request for over $100
                        million in <gloss target="#t_PL1">PL</gloss>–480 assistance.<note n="3"
                            xml:id="d256fn3">Dated November 19. (Ibid., <gloss target="#t_AID1"
                                >AID</gloss> (US) GHANA)</note> No mention made in note of book. At
                        noon briefing Nov 23, Dept spokesman confirmed protest made and <gloss
                            target="#t_PL1">PL</gloss>–480 aid refused. When asked if our <gloss
                            target="#t_PL1">PL</gloss>–480 refusal related to book’s appearance, he
                        replied “no comment.”</item>
                    <label>8.</label>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_FYI1">FYI</gloss>. If pressed for reasons why <gloss
                            target="#t_PL1">PL</gloss>–480 turned down you may say it impossible for
                        US to grant all requests for surplus food; that quantity of <gloss
                            target="#t_PL1">PL</gloss>–480 desired out of line with what we have
                        provided in other African countries of comparable population. At same time,
                        do not hide our dissatisfaction with book, or deny implication that its
                        publication could well affect our relations with Ghana. We prefer let <gloss
                            target="#t_GOG1">GOG</gloss> and others draw own conclusions. If asked
                        about this, your answer should be consistent with above.</item>
                    <label>9.</label>
                    <item>Dept considering additional measures which, if adopted, will be carefully
                        spaced and timed in order meet above objectives. End <gloss target="#t_FYI1"
                            >FYI</gloss>.</item>
                    <label>10.</label>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_INR1">INR</gloss> research memo on book being
                        pouched.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BGW1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Ball</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
